reviewText: Once upon a time in the '80s, when I was in elementary school, a film crew and Kenny Rogers invaded Buford, filming scenes of SIX PACK. I thought it was cool at the time, for I watched Erin Gray, the love interest in the film, on "Silver Spoons" and "Buck Rogers." (Little did I realize that the coolest person in the film would turn out to be Diane Lane, who would go on to get an Oscar nomination in 2003. Of course, her biggest claim-to-fame then was "A Little Romance.")When it came out months later, everyone crowded the theater to see how the whole thing came out. And it was bad. To give you an example of how bad the film was, it has a character in it named Breezy, and it's about unruly children and NASCAR racing.But the town was recognizable, so that's something interesting. I can say I've walked past the same Western Auto that Diane Lane did in that rain scene.(To see more films made in my hometown, rent Steve Martin's A SIMPLE TWIST OF FATE, which was a modern version of "Silas Marner." It bombed at the box office like this one, though the reason it bombed is because "Silas Marner" is awful.)Anyway, SIX PACK is bad.
summary: This movie is bad, but it was filmed in my hometown.

reviewText: I saw this movie on cable TV back when me and my family were the only ones on the block who had cable.  There's some fond memories tied to it.  That's why I gave it 5 stars.  Purely selfish reasons.  You should probably downgrade it 1.5 stars (making it 3.5 stars) to get a more accurate review.Six Pack reminds me of other, much better, movies such as THE BAD NEWS BEARS.  It never has the cleverness of BEARS, but it has a certain appeal that makes its downfalls forgivable.  It's biggest strength lies in the wonderful cast.  The troup of young actors come off quite well.  I couldn't keep my eyes off "Breezy".  What a doll!  I think that actress was in EDDIE AND THE CRUSERS.  Kenny Rogers was at a high point in his popularity too.  He has some good moments here.Avoid if you have really "younguns" around because of the language (which is unfortunate, since "younguns" will enjoy this most).  But if you're into family-type flicks, auto racing, or just think that Kenny Rogers is to country what Elvis was to rocknroll, then Six Pack is as good as a friday night beer buzz.
summary: Who says country singers can't act?

reviewText: The only objection I have heard to this movie, that was halfway objective, was that the attitude of the kids and language could be improved. Now I understand that judgement, but either you need to get eye surgery or or be realistic about your outlook. When I first saw this movie when it was released I fell in love with it. I'm no kid either, in fact I'm now 52. This movie is realistic and has some great acting and comedy. So if you're concerned about how it will affect kids, why don't you sit down and watch it with them. Everyone should have a laugh.It is sad to me that funny family movies like this have not come out on DVD when there is so much junk that has come out on DVD. I don't know who is keeping this from coming out on DVD but I for one will buy it when it does. I went ahead and ordered this on VHS because there is no indication that it will be on DVD anytime soon.

reviewText: If you are looking for a top-notch, action filled movie about NASCAR, this ain't it!  Kenny Rogers stars as Brewster Baker, a onetime Grand National racing star who is on the come back trail.  While Kenny Rogers is not the most talented actor, he does exuberate loads of charm in saving his newly acquired "Six Pack" of orphans from a corrupt sheriff, aptly played by Barry Corbin.  Dianne Lane and Anthony Michael Hall give great early career performances in this delightful movie.  To be fair, Robby Still's character Swifty  does swear A LOT!  But he is admonished by Brewster for his behavior.  Overall a fun movie with a little racing and a great show song, "Love Will Turn You Around" from Kenny Rogers.This movie is a bit dated but in that respect, it depicts the now mega sport in its earlier days of small dirt tracks and honestly shows where many of todays drivers get their start.  Check out the scenes from Atlanta Motor Speedway.
summary: Top notch movie for all NASCAR fans.

reviewText: I'm obviously not alone in thinking that Kenny Rogers was one of the greatest character actors of our time. Everything he did was pure gold. He can sing a little too. I run into people each day that tell me they wish they could go back and live in the 80s. I always tell them that my solution to time travel is about 4 months away, but they can capture everything great about the decade by picking up anything with Kenny Rogers. It is a lot to say one man summed up a decade, but KRog did that. One listen to Islands in the Stream by Kenny and that girl with big thingies just leaves you speechless. It's how a song should be performed. They are saying they are islands in a stream, that's all they are. Only Fish from Barney Miller said so much by saying so little and he's dead I think.Well, I know I can't do it justice(that's saying a great deal because I'm brilliant), but I'll try to sum up the sheer mass of six pack. You know how people love NASCAR all around the world now? In 1982, most people weren't aware that there was such as thing as driving in circles for hours to amuse simple minded hicks. Six pack let everyone in on the secret throught the power of pint sized Kurt Bushes and Danica Patricks. Tony Stewart would be selling appliances on street corners if it weren't for Kenny Rogers selling a country on auto racing. You know what, Enya has gotten better looking over the years, I'd probably think about doing her now. Back to Kenny, the only thing I would change about this movie would be to have him sing his lines because america, heck, the world, loves Kenny singing a tune. Well, in the end the kids win the Coke 250 by 18 laps because they develop a special fuel made of poop. It is a simple story, but your life will never be the same. Kind of like when you meet me and realize I'm a icon and you're an eskimo's stool.

reviewText: I grew up being obsessed with this movie.  My brother and I would sit, dreaming of meeting sleazy race car drivers, shocked by the one kid's trashy language "Toad suckin' honkey bum," I think it was.  I love Kenny Rogers, I, for some gross reason, find the bad guy race car driver extremely attractive, and I think the kid who sings "Good ol' Rocky Top" deserves a Grammy. I also remember loving Diane Lane (Breezy, Heather) and the kid with a lisp .  Sure, it's not a movie that makes you think much, but it sure is enjoyable for some reason.  It might just be because I grew up watching it (on Beta,) so please don't go buy it thinking it's going to be incredible.

reviewText: I saw this movie when it was originally on Pay Per View eons ago. I loved it when I was a kid, but now, I think it's a cheesy romance movie. Erin Gray (from the comedy, 'Silver Spoons') was great in this movie, and it's also one of Diane Lane's first movies, although she made others. Anyway, we all know that Kenny Rogers isn't a strong actor, but pulls this one off well. The movie is full of cursing, all done by the children played in this movie, so I wouldn't recommend this movie to kids under 13. Unless they are used to hearing such words on a daily basis, as mine aren't. This is a rags to riches movie about homeless children stealing their way to the top. Until they steal from race car driver Kenny Rogers, who then makes them work as his crew to pay off their debts to him, do they sort of change their ways. At the end it's all fairy tales and kisses as they are adopted by Kenny Rogers and his new wife Erin Gray. Full of laughes, this movie is funny, but for adults. The acting is cheesy, but remember this is an old movie, so acting isn't like it is today. The kids were great on this movie, but I think they could of done it without all the swearing, and rude acting. I guess that's what makes and sells movies though. Gone are the good old days of "nice movies" that didn't need to be previewed before showing your kids!

reviewText: The review is not necessarily about 'Six Pack', which is what it is, a nice family movie.  With the popularity of Nascar at an all time high, it's just a matter of time before Hollywood tries to remake this one, too.  The Lord knows there aren't any original ideas coming out of Tinseltown over the past decade.But anyway, if you want to see the most beautiful woman/actress/starlet/perfect creation ever to grace a movie screen, then buy this movie and watch Diane Lane over and over and over again.This film (not 'A Little Romance' when she was about 5) made me realize when I was just a little tiny lad that I was going to end up a straight guy.  I was in love with her immediately when watching this and she still looks better than any of these hags that get paid twice her salary today.Oh yeah, not only does she look her absolute best in this feature, where you'll want to watch every scene that she graces in slow motion on your DVD player, but she can act, too.  When she has the heart to heart with C Thomas Howell and then he asks her if she can see the sky when it's setting in the North and she's looking west...it's magic. Oh wait, wrong picture....but the scene where Kenny Rogers picks her up when she runs away in the rain is a true tear jerker that will capture your soul and never let go.
